measure conversion tables for distances, liquid volumes, weights, temperatu=
re, time zones, and =E2=80=9Cunofficial=E2=80=9D exchange rates, as well as=
 a 6-inch and 15 cm ruler. These rates have some historical interest for na=
tions that no longer exist, such as West Germany and the U.S.S.R.; for curr=
encies that have been merged, such as that of various Eurpoean nations; and=
 for changes in exchange rates. A sheet of instructions for the Unicon also=
 has another table of weights and measures and a list of equivalent clothin=
g sizes. The instrument and its instructions are stored in a plastic case, =
meant to be carried in the pocket of travelers.
