esults__content">
                          In the 1970s, after metric units of measure had b=
een adopted in Canada and Great Britain, some people in the United States a=
dvocated adoption of the metric system. A variety of special tables were ma=
de to help Americans convert between systems of measurement. This slide cha=
rt is one of them.
                        </dd>
                                                                      <dd c=
lass=3D" edan-search-results__content">
                          The paper cardboard sleeve is joined with adhesiv=
e and printed in red, yellow, pink, black and white. The front contains a t=
able for converting inches to millimeters, another for converting pints to =
liters, a third for converting feet to meters and a fourth for converting g=
allons to liters. The reverse has tables for miles/kilometers, ounces/grams=
, pounds/kilograms and oF/OC.
                        </dd>
                                                                      <dd c=
lass=3D" edan-search-results__content">
                          A mark on the front reads: Metrics (/) made easy.=
 Another reads: INCH/METRIC DIGITAL DIAL (/) A product of (/) Danatron (/) =
Corporation (3198 =E2=80=98C=E2=80=99, Airport Loop Drive, Costa Mesa, CA 9=
2828. A mark on the edge of the slide reads (as best as can be deciphered):=
 Copyright 1977 Nelson Taxel Woodmere N.Y. 11598 Printed in U.S.A.
                        </dd>
                                                                      <dd c=
lass=3D" edan-search-results__content">
